DID YOU KNOW: Experts estimate each household that doesn't complete the Census survey costs our community about $1,675 in local federal funding per person, per year, for 10 years. 🤑😲

Participating in the Census is a small act that can impact our community in a HUGE way!

Complete the 2020 Census by mail, by phone at 844-330-2020 or online at
http://my2020census.gov. Literally, takes 5 minutes!

post_text: Due to the magnitude of the public health and safety issues posed by COVID-19 outbreaks and contagion, OTPC has decided to make the 2020 Annual Turning Point Conference on August 25th a VIRTUAL event. As an attendee, you will still be able to meet new people, participate in discussion, watch great presenters, and receive resources to support health improvement in our state and your community! Times may be uncertain, but one thing remains true - there is power in people coming together - whether online or off! OTPC hopes you will join us for this year's virtual conference! http://okturningpoint.org/annualconference/

post_text:
HB 3028 by Representative Carol Bush is scheduled for a floor vote today! Contact your house member and let them know you support HB 3028!

HB 3028 authorizes governmental entities, religious institutions, non profit organizations, for profit companies and tribal governments to offer harm reduction services. Entities offering harm reduction services shall register with the State Department of Health and may engage in activities in order to reduce the use of drugs, prevent outbreaks of infections diseases and reduce morbidity among people who use injection drugs.

http://webserver1.lsb.state.ok.us/cf_pdf/2019-
20%20FLR/HFLR/HB3028%20HFLR.PDF

Representative Cyndi A. Munson is at Oklahoma State Capitol.
February 20 at 1:21 PM · Oklahoma City, OK ·

Today, I presented HB3640 in the House Public Safety Committee. This bill formalizes the process for implementation and statewide training of the Handle With Care program. Handle With Care is a program aimed at ensuring that children who are exposed to a traumatic event receive appropriate interventions so they can succeed in school to the best of their ability.

I am so grateful for the Members of the House Public Safety Committee for supporting children who have experienced a traumatic event. Together, we are helping law enforcement agencies and school districts have the resources and interventions they need to help children in their communities.

HB3640 passed with a 12-1 vote and will now head to the House Floor for a hearing! #okleg
text:
Exciting news! Thank you Representative Cyndi Munson for your leadership! "Handle With Care" is a great initiative!

I am so grateful for the Members of the House Public Safety Committee for supporting children who have experienced a traumatic event. Together, we are helping law enforcement agencies and school districts have the resources and interventions they need to help children in their communities.

You're Invited to "A Healthy Workforce Luncheon" on Tuesday, June 25, 2019 from 11:30 a.m. to 1 p.m. Vast 50th floor, Devon Tower - 333 W Sheridan Ave, OKC. $15 Registration Fee.

Learn why Oklahoma needs a smokefree indoor air law and how this small change will ultimately benefit Oklahoma businesses and the health of their workers.

Keynote Speaker: Sharon Eubanks, Vice-Chair, Board of Directors, Americans for Nonsmokers' Rights
Panelists: Leslie Osborn,Labor Commissioner, State of Oklahoma; Kat Peckenpaugh,Owner, Kat's Tavern; and
Moderator: Mary Blankenship, Pointer Senior Vice President

To register and pay visit https://www.occhd.org/payment

FY 2019 Funding Opportunity Announcement

The Office of Minority Health (OMH) at the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services administers grant programs to support projects that implement innovative models to improve minority health and reduce health disparities. The YES Initiative seeks to support projects that address the HHS priority to expand youth participation in sports and encourage regular physical activity, especially for youth populations with lower rates of sports participation and communities with limited access to athletic facilities or recreational areas. Application Due Date: May 31, 2019
https://www.grants.gov/web/grants/view-opportunity.html?oppId=314361&utm_medium=email&utm_source=govdelivery

August 20, 2018 at 8:12 AM ·

Did you know that the majority of people served by the state's two food banks are chronically hungry children, seniors on fixed incomes and hard working families who cannot make ends meet? PLEASE JOIN THE OTPC IN FIGHTING HUNGER IN OKLAHOMA!

Turning Point Conference attendees are asked to donate the MOST NEEDED items for the food banks:
•Canned goods (meat, vegetables, fruit, tuna)
•Packaged goods (peanut butter, rice, beans)
•Personal hygiene products
•Cleaning supplies
•Paper goods

For every item donated, the conference attendee/donor will receive a ticket for a chance at several great door prizes! Must be present to win! Donations will be accepted from 7:30 AM to 5:00 PM on Thursday, August 30th at the Conference Center Resource Room - Moore Norman Technology Center South Penn Campus.

For more information visit: http://okturningpoint.org/annualconference/serviceproject/

Oklahoma State Department of Health
August 7, 2018 at 8:45 AM ·

Community leaders, public health professionals, advocates and members of the public are invited to the Annual Turning Point Conference and Policy Day, Aug. 30, at the Moore Norman Technology Center, South Penn Campus, in Oklahoma City.

The keynote speaker is Dr. Nathan Mellor, president of Strata Leadership, LLC of Oklahoma City. Conference breakout sessions will cover topics such as teen pregnancy prevention, opioid abuse prevention, paid family leave and school health.

All attendees must register online by 5 p.m. Thursday, Aug. 23, as onsite registration is not available. Registration is $85 and includes lunch.
Learn more here: https://go.usa.gov/xU7fm

As part of the Farm Bill, the House is looking at implementing significant changes to SNAP that will be harmful to Oklahoma families.
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSe0H63k1l4PL8FQRchGh3Hc2Ep3dUD5b4ZsLPe0CY-GPo0iMw/viewform
shared_text:
DOCS.GOOGLE.COM
Sign on Letter: Protect SNAP in the 2018 Farm Bill
text:
Hunger Free Oklahoma, Regional Food Bank of Oklahoma and Community Food Bank of Eastern Oklahoma are circulating a sign-on letter to collect signatures from organizations in Representative Lucas's (Chair of the House Agriculture Commitee) district - to ask him to consider the importance of SNAP to families in his district. As part of the Farm Bill, the House is looking at implementing significant changes to SNAP that will be harmful to Oklahoma families.

Oklahomans for Paid Family Leave
March 13, 2018 at 9:56 PM ·

SB 1581 has passed TWO committees: Retirement and Appropriations UNANIMOUSLY!!

The bill would allow state employees to donate leave to a bank. This bank would only be available if all other paid leave is exhausted and only for an FMLA qualifying event. Parents are an exception and don’t have to exhaust their sick leave. This bill also intentionally includes care for military service members.

This would ensure that our state employees could be there for their families when they are needed most.
